description.other_contributors: Koray Atalag, University of Auckland, New Zealand

details.purpose: To record observations on a blood film including microscopic findings and cell counts.
details.use: Will normally be reported back to the requesting clinician within the context of an overall Composition-based laboratory report.
details.misuse: This archetype is not a full laboratory report and requires diagnosis and other assessments to be recorded using other archetypes.

items.items: To record the result of a laboratory test which may be used to record a single valued test but will often be specialised or templated to represent multiple value or 'panel' tests. This archetype also acts as the parent for specialisations appropriate for more specific laboratory tests microbiology, histopathology.
The full blood count or examination normally reported by a haematology laboratory.

Specific identifier for this lab test. e.g. Full blood count , blood glucose, urine microbiology. May equate to the result name for a single value result. Commonly a coded term e.g from LOINC or SNOMED-CT.
Representations of the whole test in mutlimedia e.g image, audio, video.
Unique identifiers used in delivery of the care process.
Demographic details of the laboratory with responsibility for the test. Details of secondary laboratories may also be included.
This is an initial or interim result - further updates are anticipated
This is the final result. No further alterations are anticipated
This is a supplememtary result in addition to the Interim result
This is a Correction which should replace any previous results
An overall interpretative comment on this test.
The ID assigned to the order by the order requester. Equivalent to the NEHTA Requester Order Identifier.
The ID assigned to the test order by the order filler, usually by the (LIS) Laboratory Information System. Equivalent to the DICOM Accession Number and NEHTA Laboratory Request Identifier.
Details of the specimen being reported where all individual results are derived from the same specimen
The identifier given to the laboratory test result of a pathology investigation.
The status of the lab test as a whole.
The date and/or time that the result was issued for the recorded test status.
The date and time related to the results status is useful for version control and cumulative results for the report.
The type of high-level diagnostic service e.g. biochemistry, haematology.
The variation in red cell volume
The velocity of sedimentation of red cells in the first hour
The number of platelets per litre
The number of white cells per litre
The differential count of white cells or leukocytes
The number of neutrophils per litre
The number of lymphocytes per litre
The number of basophils per litre
The number of monocytes per litre
The number of eosinophils per litre
The proportion of the volume of blood taken up by platelets
The features of the blood film on microscopy
The number of red blood cells per litre
(Haematocrit) The proportion of the volume of blood taken up by red blood cells
The average haemaglobin concentration in the red blood cells
The average volume of the red blood cells (PCV/RCC)
The average haemaglobin content of red blood cells
Slot to allow an annotation to be added to a particular test result at run-time.
